data.title: Athletes Born on May 23
data.meta_description: Famous birthdays in sport for the 23rd of May. Browse birthdays of sports stars, managers and coaches that were born on May 23.
data.text:
William "Dummy" Hoy, American baseball outfielder (most accomplished deaf player in MLB history; NL stolen base leader 1888; Washington Senators, Cincinnati Reds), born in Houcktown, Ohio (d. 1961)

Dezső Lauber, Hungarian competitive athlete (Ice skating, golf, tennis, cycling), and architect, born in Pecs, Hungary (d. 1966)

Zack Wheat, American Baseball Hall of Fame outfielder (NL batting champion 1918; Brooklyn Superbas / Dodgers / Robins 1909–26), born in Hamilton, Missouri (d. 1972)

Rafael Moreno Aranzadi [Pichichi], Spanish soccer forward (5 caps; Athletic Bilbao), born in Bilbao, Spain (d. 1922)

Betty Nuthall

English tennis player (US National Championship, 1930), born in Surbiton, England

Dennis Compton, England cricket batsman and footballer (5,807 Test runs, Arsenal 1950 FA Cup), born in Hendon, England (d. 1997)

Nirode Chowdhury, Indian cricket medium pace bowler (2 Tests, 1 wicket; Bengal, Bihar), born in Jharkhand, India (d. 1979)

Clyde King, American baseball pitcher, coach, manager and executive (Brooklyn Dodgers; New York Yankees), born in Goldsboro, North Carolina (d. 2010)

Buster Welch, American cutting horse trainer (4 x NCHA World Championship; 5 x NCHA World Championship Futurity), born in Sterling City Texas (d. 2022)

1928 Nina Otkalenko, Soviet Russian 800m runner (9 world records; European Champion, 1954), born in Kursk, Russia, USSR (d. 2015)

Vic Stasiuk, Canadian ice hockey left winger (Chicago Black Hawks, Detroit Red Wings, Boston Bruins) and coach (Philadelphia Flyers, Vancouver Canucks), born in Lethbridge, Alberta (d. 2023)

Mason Rudolph, American golfer (Ryder Cup 1971; PGA C'ship 1973 3rd), born in Clarksville, Tennessee (d. 2011)

1934 Syd Millar, Irish rugby union prop (37 Tests Ireland; 9 British & Irish Lions; Ballymena RFC, Ulster), coach (Ireland, B&I Lions 1974) and executive (IRFU President 1995-96), born in Ballymena, Northern Ireland (d. 2023)

Robert Sangster, British race horse owner and breeder, born in Liverpool, England (d. 2004)

John Newcombe

Australian tennis player (7 Grand Slam singles, 17 Grand Slam doubles titles), born in Sydney, Australia

David Graham, Australian golfer (PGA C'ship 1979, US Open 1981), born in Windsor, NSW

Ernesto Marcel, Panamanian boxer (WBA featherweight title 1972-74), born in Colón, Panama (d. 2020)

Aleksandr Klepikov, Russian rower (Olympic gold Soviet Union coxed four 1976), born in St. Petersburg, Russia (d. 2021)

Anatoly Karpov

Russian chess player (world champion 1975-85, 93-99), born in Zlatoust, Russia

'Marvelous' Marvin Hagler, American boxer (undisputed World Middleweight champion 1980-87; second-longest unified C'ship reign in history), born in Newark, New Jersey (d. 2021)

Buck Showalter, American baseball manager (AL Manager of the Year 1994, 2004, 14; NY Yankees, Arizona Diamondbacks, Texas Rangers, Baltimore Orioles) and analyst (ESPN, YES network), born in DeFuniak Springs, Florida

1956 Mark Shaw, New Zealand rugby union flanker (30 caps; Manawatu, Hawke's Bay), born in Palmerston North, New Zealand

Marcella Mesker, Netherlands, tennis star

Dave Babych, Edmonton, NHL defenseman (Vancouver Canucks)

1961 Kevin Romine, baseball player

Kenny Gattison, NBA forward (Orlando Magic)

James Hasty, NFL cornerback (KC Chiefs)

1965 Manuel Sanchís Hontiyuelo, Real Madrid footballer

1965 Woorkeri Venkat Raman, cricketer (Indian slow left-arm all-rounder)

Gary Roberts, Canadian ice hockey left wing (NHL All-Star 1992, 93, 2004; Calgary Flames, Carolina Hurricanes, Toronto Maple Leafs), born in North York, Ontario

1966 Graeme Hick, English cricket batsman (65 Tests, 6 x 100s; 120 ODIs; Worcestershire), born in Harare, Zimbabwe

Craig Monk, New Zealand sailor (Olympic Finn class bronze 1992; America's Cup), born in Auckland, New Zealand

Pat Hurst, American golfer (ANA Inspiration 1998), born in San Leandro, California

1969 Ramon Caraballo, baseball player

Bryan Herta, American race car driver

1970 Ricky Gutierrez, infielder (Houston Astros), born in Miami, Florida

Issac Booth, NFL cornerback/safety (Cleveland Browns)

1971 Joseph Rogers, CFL receiver (Winnipeg Blue Bombers)

1971 Marshall Boze, pitcher (Milwaukee Brewers), born in San Manual, Arizona

Isabelle Fijalkowski, WNBA center/forward (Cleveland Rockers)

1972 Rene Ingoglia, running back (Buffalo Bills)

1972 Rubens Barrichello, Brazilian formula one driver

Duane Clemons, American NFL linebacker (Minnesota Vikings), born in Riverside, California

1974 Matt Hindle, Canadian bobsledder, born in Calgary, Alberta

Vincent Goossens, soccer player (Dordrecht '90)

Ricardinho, Brazilian footballer

Carolyn Moos, American model and professional basketball player

1978 Mike González, American baseball player, born in Corpus Christi, Texas

Kirk Saarloos, American baseball player

Theofanis Gekas, Greek footballer

Cyrill Gloor, Swiss footballer

Ross Wallace, Scottish footballer

Ruben Zadkovich, Australian soccer player

Morgan Pressel, American golfer (ANA Inspiration 2007), born in Tampa, Florida

Aaron Donald, American NFL football defensive end, Defensive Rookie of the Year, 7x Pro Bowls, 3x Defensive Player of the Year (St. Louis/Los Angeles Rams), born in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania
